What is a Spring IOC Container?
Ans:Inversion of Control (IoC) is a design principle where
control of object creation and managing is taken care of by
container. Instead of a developer directly instantiating objects
and managing their dependencies, the framework manages this
process. This allows for loose coupling between components,
easier testing, and greater flexibility in the application's
architecture.
The Spring Frameworks IoC container simplifies this process by
taking over the responsibility of creating and managing objects.
You simply tell Spring what objects you need, and it will create
them for you and provide them to your code. This is called
dependency injection.
SPRING TECHIE
3.What is a Spring IOC Container?
Ans: The org. springframework.context.ApplicationContext
interface represents the Spring IoC container and is responsible
for instantiating, configuring, and assembling the beans.
The container gets its instructions on what objects to
instantiate, configure, and assemble by reading configuration
metadata(xml file).
The configuration metadata is represented in XML, Java
annotations, or Java code.It lets you express the objects that
compose your application and the rich interdependencies between
those objects.

5.What is Dependency injection?
Dependency Injection (DI) is a software design pattern that
allows components to be loosely coupled, making it easier to
test, maintain, and extend the system.
Suppose classA depends on classB, in traditional way we create
the object of classB which is a leads to
Tight Coupling: Components are closely tied together, making it
difficult to change one component without affecting others.
Rigidity: Changes to one component can break other components.
Fragility: Small changes can have significant impacts on the
system
In contrast, Dependency Injection (DI) decouples components by
providing dependencies through a third-party mechanism, such as
a container or framework. This allows components to be more
flexible, modular, and reusable.
Benefits of Dependency Injection:
Loose Coupling: Components are decoupled, making it easier to change or replace dependencies
without affecting the component.
SPRING TECHIE
Testability: Components are easier to test, as dependencies can be mocked or stubbed.
Reusability: Components can be reused in different contexts, as dependencies can be easily swapped
or replaced.
Extensibility: The system is more extensible, as new dependencies can be added or replaced without
modifying existing components.

7.What are the types of dependency injection.
There are mainly three types of dependency injection.
1. Constructor Injection:
In constructor injection, dependencies are provided
through a class constructor.
Benefits:
SPRING TECHIE
Dependencies are explicitly declared as part of
the class's constructor signature, making it
clear what dependencies are required.
It ensures that the object is fully initialized
with all its dependencies at the time of
creation, resulting in objects that are
immediately ready for use.
Constructor injection makes it easier to enforce
the principle of immutability, as dependencies
can be marked as final.
2. Setter Injection:
In setter injection, dependencies are provided through
setter methods.
Benefits:
Setter injection provides flexibility by allowing
dependencies to be changed or updated after the
object has been created.
It can be useful in scenarios where some
dependencies are optional or can be changed
dynamically at runtime.
It allows for circular dependencies to be
resolved more easily, as setter methods can be
called after the objects have been created.
3. Field Injection:
In field injection, dependencies are directly assigned
to class fields.
Benefits:
Field injection is concise and requires less code
compared to constructor or setter injection.
It is often used in frameworks like Spring, where
dependencies are automatically injected based on
annotations, reducing the need for boilerplate
code.
SPRING TECHIE
Field injection can be suitable for simple
scenarios where dependencies are straightforward
and unlikely to change.
8.Which one is better: Constructor-based or
setter-based DI?
It is a good practice to use constructor injection for
mandatory dependencies and setter methods for optional
dependencies.
The Spring team generally advocates constructor injection, as it lets you
implement application components as immutable objects and ensures that
required dependencies are not null.

12.How Component Scanning(@ComponentScan)
Works?
Annotation Discovery: The Spring Framework uses annotation-based
configuration to identify Spring beans. It scans the specified
packages and subpackages for classes annotated with @Component,
@Service, @Repository, @Controller, or other stereotype
annotations that indicate a beans role in the application.
Annotation Declaration: The @ComponentScan annotation is typically
declared in a configuration class. This configuration class can
be annotated with @Configuration or @SpringBootApplication (in a
Spring Boot application).
@Configuration
@ComponentScan(basePackages = "com.example")
public class AppConfig {
}
During the application startup, Spring scans the specified packages and
their sub-packages for classes annotated with stereotype annotations such
as @Component, @Service, @Repository, and @Controller.
For each class annotated with a stereotype annotation, Spring creates a
bean definition and registers the bean in the application context.
Execution Flow:
Application StartupComponent ScanningBean DetectionBean
RegistrationBean Initialization

17.What are Bean scopes?
In the same way in Java we have variable scope ,like in spring
framework we have bean scope.
In Spring Framework, a bean scope defines the lifecycle and the
visibility of a bean within the Spring IoC container. Spring
Framework provides several built-in bean scopes, each with a
specific purpose and behavior.
Singleton:(Default) creates a single bean definition to a single
object instance for each Spring IoC container.
Prototype:: Creates a new bean instance every time the bean is
requested.
Request:creates a single bean definition to the lifecycle of a
single HTTP request. That is, each HTTP request has its own
instance of a bean created off the back of a single bean
definition. Only valid in the context of a web-aware Spring
ApplicationContext.
Session: creates a single bean definition to the lifecycle of an
HTTP Session. Only valid in the context of a web-aware Spring
ApplicationContext.
Application:creates a single bean definition to the lifecycle of a
ServletContext. Only valid in the context of a web-aware Spring
ApplicationContext.
SPRING TECHIE
Websocket:creates a single bean definition to the lifecycle of a
WebSocket. Only valid in the context of a web-aware Spring
ApplicationContext.
18.What is the Spring bean lifecycle?
The Spring bean lifecycle can be divided into three phases:
instantiation, configuration, and destruction.(It is managed by
IOC)
Instantiation: The Spring container creates an instance of the
bean using the no-argument constructor or a constructor
specified via dependency injection.
Populating Properties: The container populates the bean's
properties using dependency injection. This includes setting up
dependencies as defined in the configuration.
Destruction:When the application context is closed, the bean is
destroyed.
19.Lazy Loading vs. Eager Loading?
In Spring, beans are lazy-loaded or eager-loaded. Lazy loading means that a
bean is not created until it is first requested by the application. Eager
loading means that a bean is created when the application starts up.
Eager loading can be useful for beans that are needed by the
application as soon as it starts up.
For example, an application might need to connect to a database as
soon as it starts up. In this case, it would make sense to eagerly
load the bean that is responsible for connecting to the database.
SPRING TECHIE

21.What is meant by Autowiring?
Autowiring is a feature in Spring, which allows the container to
automatically resolve and inject dependencies into required
classes.
22.What are the Types of Autowiring?
1.no(default):
This is the default setting, which means autowiring is not
used. Dependencies must be explicitly wired using <property> and
<constructor-arg> elements in the configuration.
2.byName:
This mode injects the dependency based on the name of the
property. The Spring container looks for a bean with the
same name as the property to be autowired.
3.byType:
SPRING TECHIE
This mode injects the dependency based on the type of the
property. The Spring container looks for a bean of the same
type as the property to be autowired. If there is more than
one bean of the same type, an error is thrown.
4.constructor:
This mode injects dependencies via the constructor. The
Spring container looks for the constructor with arguments
and resolves the dependencies based on the type. If there
are multiple constructors, it tries to match the
parameters.
23.How @Autowire annotation works?
The @Autowired annotation works by using reflection to find the
appropriate dependency to inject. It will first look for a bean
with the same type as the dependency. If it cannot find a bean
of the same type, it will look for a bean with a qualifier that
matches the name of the dependency. If it still cannot find a
bean to inject, it will throw an exception.
24.How @Inject annotation works and
differences between @Autowired and @Inject.
The @Inject annotation is a standard JSR-330 annotation. It is used to
inject dependencies into beans that are managed by any dependency
injection container that supports JSR-330. The @Inject annotation can
only be used with byType and byName autowiring
The difference between them is @Autowired used in Spring Container and
@Inject used in injection containers that support JSR-330.
25.How to exclude a Bean from Autowiring?

2.Disabling auto-configuration for a specific bean:In Spring

{MyConfiguration.class}) to exclude a specific
auto-configuration class.

26.Explain what is MVC?
MVC is an abbreviation for Model, View, and Controller. The MVC
architectural pattern separates an application into three
components Model, View, and Controller. In this pattern, the
model represents the shape of the data and business logic. It
maintains and preserves the data of the application. Model
objects retrieve and store model state in a database. The view
is basically and technically a user interface. The view segment
displays the data-using model to the user and also enables them
to modify the data. The controller is the part, which handles
the user request.
SPRING TECHIE

Spring MVC architecture consists of several key components:

32.How MVC picks up a view?
1. Request Handling: When a request is made to a Spring MVC
application, it is intercepted by the DispatcherServlet.
This servlet acts as the front controller, delegating the
request to the appropriate controller based on the request
URL.
SPRING TECHIE
2. Controller Method Execution: The designated controller
method processes the request, preparing the model data and
determining the view name. It returns this information
encapsulated in a ModelAndView object or as a view name
string with model data.
3. ViewResolver: The DispatcherServlet then uses one or more
configured ViewResolver beans to resolve the view name to
an actual view. This process involves:
Looking up the view name in the registered ViewResolver
instances.Each ViewResolver checks if it can resolve the
given view name to a concrete view. Common ViewResolver
implementations include InternalResourceViewResolver,
ThymeleafViewResolver, and BeanNameViewResolver.
4. Rendering the View: Once the ViewResolver resolves the view
name to a concrete view, the DispatcherServlet renders the
view. This involves passing the model data to the view,
which then generates the HTML response (or another format,
like JSON) sent back to the client.
33.How ViewResolver knows the extension of the
file?
Each ViewResolver has its own strategy for resolving views. For
example:
InternalResourceViewResolver: Maps logical view names to
JSP files or other server-side templates.
UrlBasedViewResolver: Resolves views based on URLs or
patterns.
XmlViewResolver: Resolves views based on XML
configurations.
Example:
<bean id="viewResolver"
class="org.springframework.web.servlet.view.InternalResourceView
Resolver">
<property name="prefix" value="/WEB-INF/views/" />
<property name="suffix" value=".jsp" />
SPRING TECHIE
</bean>
The prefix specifies where to look for view files relative to
the web application root.
The suffix specifies the file extension of the view files (in
this case, .jsp).
The InternalResourceViewResolver allows Spring MVC to resolve
logical view names (e.g., "home") to specific JSP files located
in /WEB-INF/views/, effectively providing a way to separate view
logic from business logic in a web application.

<%@ page language="java" contentType="text/html; charset=UTF-8"

private static final String UPLOAD_DIR = "/path/to/upload/directory/";
@PostMapping("/upload")
public String handleFileUpload(@RequestParam("file") MultipartFile file, Model
model) {
if (!file.isEmpty()) {
try {
// Ensure the directory exists
File uploadDir = new File(UPLOAD_DIR);
if (!uploadDir.exists()) {
uploadDir.mkdirs(); // create the directory if it doesn't exist
}
// Get the file and save it
byte[] bytes = file.getBytes();
String filePath = UPLOAD_DIR + file.getOriginalFilename();
try (OutputStream outputStream = new FileOutputStream(filePath)) {
outputStream.write(bytes);
}
model.addAttribute("message", "File uploaded successfully: " +
file.getOriginalFilename());
} catch (IOException e) {
model.addAttribute("message", "Failed to upload file: " +
file.getOriginalFilename());
}
} else {
model.addAttribute("message", "Failed to upload empty file.");
}
return "uploadResult";

39.Explain the difference between
HandlerMapping and HandlerAdapter in Spring
MVC?
HandlerMapping: Responsible for mapping incoming requests to
appropriate handler methods (controllers). It determines which
controller should process a particular request based on the URL
pattern or other criteria.
HandlerAdapter: Responsible for invoking the actual handler
method (controller method) once it's determined by the
HandlerMapping. It adapts the handler method's signature to
handle the HTTP request and response.
SPRING TECHIE
40.Explain the difference between forwarding
and redirecting in Spring MVC. When would you
use each approach?
Forwarding: Involves transferring control from one servlet to
another within the same server without the client being
informed. It's achieved using RequestDispatcher.forward() and is
typically used for internal processing.
Redirecting: Involves sending a redirect HTTP status code (302)
to the client, which then sends a new request to a different
URL. It's achieved using redirect: prefix or RedirectAttributes
and is used to redirect the client to a new resource.
Usage: Use forwarding when you want to handle multiple requests
internally within the server. Use redirecting when you want the
client's browser to issue a new request to a different URL.
41.What is the stateless bean in
spring? name it and explain it.
A stateless bean in Spring Framework is a bean that does
not maintain any state between method invocations. This
means that the bean does not store any information about
the previous invocations, and each method call is handled
independently.
Stateless beans are typically used for services that
perform actions or calculations, but do not maintain any
state between invocations. This can include services that
perform mathematical calculations, access external
SPRING TECHIE
resources, or perform other tasks that do not require the
bean to maintain state.
Stateless beans can be implemented as singleton beans, and
multiple clients can share the same instance of the bean.
Since stateless beans do not maintain any state, they can
be easily scaled horizontally by adding more instances of
the bean to handle the increased load.
42.Can a singleton bean scope handle
multiple parallel requests?
A singleton bean in Spring has a single instance that is shared
across all requests, regardless of the number of parallel
requests. This means that if two requests are processed
simultaneously, they will share the same bean instance and
access to the beans state will be shared among the requests.
However, its important to note that if the singleton bean is
stateful, and the state is shared among requests, this could
lead to race conditions and other concurrency issues. For
example, if two requests are trying to modify the same piece of
data at the same time, it could lead to data inconsistencies.
To avoid these issues, its important to make sure that any
stateful singleton beans are designed to be thread-safe. One way
to do this is to use synchronization or other concurrency
control mechanisms such as the synchronized keyword, Lock or
ReentrantLock classes, or the @Transactional annotation if the
bean is performing database operations.
43.What if we call a singleton bean from
prototype or prototype bean from singleton
How many objects returned?
Singleton Bean
SPRING TECHIE
A singleton bean is created once per Spring IoC container and
shared among all clients requesting it. Any requests to this
bean will return the same instance.
Prototype Bean
A prototype bean is created every time it is requested. Each
request for this bean results in a new instance.
Scenario 1: Calling a Singleton Bean from a Prototype Bean
When a prototype bean depends on a singleton bean, every
instance of the prototype bean will share the same instance of
the singleton bean.
Prototype Bean A ----> Singleton Bean S
Prototype Bean B ----> Singleton Bean S
Prototype Bean C ----> Singleton Bean S
Prototype Bean Instances: A, B, C (different instances)
Singleton Bean Instances: S (same instance shared)
Scenario 2: Calling a Prototype Bean from a Singleton Bean
On the other hand, if a prototype bean is injected into a
singleton bean, then each time the singleton bean is called, a
new instance of the prototype bean will be created.

45.Describe Spring AOP?
Spring AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming) is a powerful feature
of the Spring Framework that enables the modularization of
concerns that cut across multiple classes or layers of an
application, such as transaction management, logging, security,
and more. AOP helps in separating cross-cutting concerns from
the business logic, making the code more modular, readable, and
maintainable.
46.Difference between Concern and
Cross-cutting Concern in Spring AOP?
A Concern is a behavior that we want to have in an application
module. Concerns may be defined as functionality we want to
implement to solve a specific business problem. For example in
any eCommerce application, different concerns (or modules) may
be inventory management, shipping management, user management
etc.
A cross-cutting concern is a concern that is applicable
throughout the application (or more than one module). e.g.
logging, security and data transfer are the concerns needed in
almost every module of an application, hence they are termed as
cross-cutting concerns.
SPRING TECHIE

48.Key Concepts of Spring AOP?
Aspect: A module that encapsulates a cross-cutting concern. An
aspect can contain multiple pieces of advice.
Advice: Action taken by an aspect at a particular join point.
Types of advice include:
Before: Executed before a join point.
After: Executed after a join point.
After Returning: Executed after a join point completes
normally.
After Throwing: Executed if a method exits by throwing an
exception.
Around: Surrounds a join point (combines before and after
advice).
Join Point: A point during the execution of a program, such as
the execution of a method or handling an exception, where an
aspect can be applied.
Pointcut: A predicate that matches join points. Advice is
associated with a pointcut expression and runs at any join point
matched by the pointcut.
Introduction: Adding new methods or fields to existing classes.
Target Object: The object being advised by one or more aspects.
It is also referred to as the proxied object.
SPRING TECHIE
Weaving: The process of linking aspects with other application
types or objects to create an advised object. Weaving can be
done at compile time, load time, or runtime.

What are the features of SpringBoot over spring
framework?
Spring Boot is a popular framework in the Spring ecosystem that provides a set
of features and benefits over the traditional Spring framework. Here are some of
the key features and advantages of Spring Boot over the core Spring framework:
1. Auto-Configuration: Spring Boot offers a wide range of
auto-configuration options, which means it can
automatically configure the Spring application context
based on the projects dependencies. This eliminates
much of the manual configuration required in a typical
Spring application.
2. Standalone: Spring Boot applications are standalone by
default, which means they include an embedded web server
(e.g., Tomcat, Jetty, or Undertow). This simplifies the
deployment process and reduces the need for external web
servers.
SPRING TECHIE
3. Opinionated Defaults: Spring Boot provides sensible
default configurations for various aspects, like data
source setup, view resolution, and more. However, you
can easily override these defaults when needed.
4. Microservices-Ready: Spring Boot is well-suited for
building microservices and cloud-native applications. It
offers features like externalized configuration, service
discovery, and distributed tracing.
5. Production-Ready: Spring Boot includes built-in
production-ready features such as health checks,
metrics, and monitoring, making it easier to manage and
monitor your applications.
6. Spring-boot starter dependencies:These simplify the
process of adding common dependencies to your Spring
Boot application by bundling a group of commonly used
libraries into a single starter dependency. This helps
to reduce the amount of configuration and dependency
management needed in your project.

63.Explain Spring Boot Architecture?
We can mainly divide Spring boot into 3 layers,
Controller classes as the presentation layer. Keep this
layer as thin as possible and limited to the mechanics of
the MVC operations, e.g., receiving and validating the
inputs, manipulating the model object, returning the
appropriate ModelAndView object, and so on. All the
business-related operations should be done in the service
SPRING TECHIE
classes. Controller classes are usually put in a controller
package.
Service classes as the business logic layer. Calculations,
data transformations, data processes, and cross-record
validations (business rules) are usually done at this
layer. They get called by the controller classes and might
call repositories or other services. Service classes are
usually put in a service package.
Repository classes as data access layer. This layers
responsibility is limited to Create, Retrieve, Update, and
Delete (CRUD) operations on a data source, which is usually
a relational or non-relational database. Repository classes
are usually put in a repository package.

64.What is the Java Persistence API?
JPA stands for Jakarta Persistence API (JPA), formerly known as
Java Persistence API.
JPA is just a specification that facilitates object-relational
mapping to manage relational data in Java applications. It
provides a platform to work directly with objects instead of
using SQL statements.
JPA defines only specifications, it does not provide an
implementation. JPA implementation is provided as a reference
implementation by the vendors developing O/R Mappers such as
Hibernate, EclipseLink, and Apache OpenJPA.
65.What is Object-Relational Mapping?
The term Object/Relational Mapping refers to the technique of
mapping data from an object model representation to a relational
data model representation (and vice versa).
For example, let's look at the below diagram showing the mapping
between the Student java model and the database relational
student table.
SPRING TECHIE
66.What is the Difference Between JPA and
Hibernate?
As we know that JPA is just a specification, meaning there is no
implementation. You can annotate your classes as much as you
would like with JPA annotations, however, without an
implementation, nothing will happen. Think of JPA as the
guidelines that must be followed or an interface, while
Hibernate's JPA implementation is code that meets the API as
defined by the JPA specification and provides the under-the-hood
functionality.
In short, JPA is the interface while Hibernate is the
implementation.
67.Defining a JPA Entity Class?
A JPA entity class is a POJO (Plain Old Java Object) class, i.e. an ordinary Java class
that is marked (annotated) as having the ability to represent objects in the database.
Every class should must be annotated with @Entity and one field
should be marked as @Id(PrimaryKey) it means primary key of
table. All others are optional fields. When you run the
application , JPA will create a table with variables declared.
@Entity
@Table(name = "students")
public class Student {
@Id

68.What are the different types of entity
mapping?
Following are the types of object-relational mapping: -
One-to-one mapping: The one-to-one mapping represents a
single-valued association where an instance of one entity
is associated with an instance of another entity. In this
type of association, one instance of the source entity can
be mapped with at most one instance of the target entity.
One-To-Many mapping: The One-To-Many mapping comes into the
category of collection-valued association where an entity
is associated with a collection of other entities. In this
type of association, the instance of one entity can be
mapped with any number of instances of another entity.
Many-to-one mapping: The Many-To-One mapping represents a
single-valued association where a collection of entities
can be associated with a similar entity. In the relational
database, more than one row of an entity can refer to the
same row of another entity.
SPRING TECHIE
Many-to-many mapping: The Many-To-Many mapping represents a
collection-valued association where any number of entities
can be associated with a collection of other entities. In
the relational database, more than one row of one entity
can refer to more than one row of another entity.
69.What are the JPA Cascade Types?
JPA allows you to propagate the state transition from a parent
entity to a child. For this purpose, the JPA
javax.persistence.CascadeType defines various cascade types:
ALL - cascades all entity state transitions
PERSIST - cascades the entity persist operation.
MERGE - cascades the entity merge operation.
REMOVE - cascades the entity remove operation.
REFRESH - cascades the entity refresh operation.
DETACH - cascades the entity detach operation.
Entities that use relationships often have dependencies on the
existence of the other entity in the relationship. For example,
a line item is part of an order; if the order is deleted, the
line item also should be deleted. This is called a cascade
delete relationship.
SPRING TECHIE
70. What are the JPA Primary Key Generation
Strategies?
The JPA specification supports 4 different primary key
generation strategies which generate the primary key values
programmatically or use database features, like auto-incremented
columns or sequences.
1. GenerationType.AUTO
2. GenerationType.IDENTITY
3. GenerationType.SEQUENCE
4.GenerationType.TABLE
71.What Is the Embeddable Class in JPA?
An embeddable class is a class that is not used by itself, only
as part of one or more Entity classes. An entity class can
contain both single embedded classes and collections of such
classes. Also, such classes can be used as keys or map values.
At runtime, each embedded class belongs to only one object of
the Entity class and cannot be used to transfer data between the
objects of the Entity classes (that is, such a class is not a
common data structure for different objects).
In general, such a class serves to make the definition of common
attributes for several entities, we can assume that JPA simply
embeds into the Entity instead of an object of this class, the
attributes it contains.

75.What is the difference between
CrudRepository and JpaRepository? When
would you use one over the other?
CrudRepository provides basic CRUD operations (save,
findById, findAll, deleteById, etc.).
JpaRepository extends PagingAndSortingRepository, which in
turn extends CrudRepository. It provides JPA-specific
methods like flush, saveAndFlush, and deleteInBatch.
Additionally, JpaRepository includes methods for pagination
and sorting.
Use CrudRepository for simple CRUD operations when you do
not need pagination and sorting.
Use JpaRepository when you need advanced JPA features,
including pagination, sorting, and batch operations.
76.How does Spring Data JPA handle the N+1
select problem? How can you solve it?
The N+1 select problem occurs when fetching a collection of
entities and their related entities results in multiple
additional queries (one for each related entity)
Lazy Loading: By default, JPA uses lazy loading, which can cause
the N+1 problem.
Eager Loading: Changing the fetch type to eager can prevent N+1
issues but may lead to performance problems due to large joins.
JPQL Fetch Joins: Using JPQL fetch joins can solve the N+1 problem
by fetching associations in a single query.
SPRING TECHIE
@Query("SELECT u FROM User u JOIN FETCH u.roles WHERE
u.id = :id") User findByIdWithRoles(@Param("id") Long
id);
77.Explain the concept of "Derived Query
Methods" in Spring Data JPA. How are they
generated?
Derived query methods are automatically generated queries based
on method names in repository interfaces. The method name
contains the query logic and is parsed by Spring Data JPA to
generate the appropriate query.
The query is generated by analyzing the method name and mapping
it to the entitys fields and repositorys entity class.
List<User> findByLastName(String lastName);
User findByEmailAndFirstName(String email, String firstName);
78.What is the difference between @Query
annotation and named queries?
@Query Annotation: Allows you to define a JPQL or native SQL
query directly on the repository method. It provides flexibility
and is easier for quick and dynamic queries.
@Query("SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.email = :email")
User findByEmail(@Param("email") String email);
SPRING TECHIE
Named Queries: Defined statically at the entity level using
@NamedQuery or @NamedNativeQuery annotations. They are compiled
when the session factory is initialized, providing better
performance for frequently used queries.
@Entity
@NamedQuery(name = "User.findByEmail", query = "SELECT u FROM
User u WHERE u.email = :email")
public class User { ... }
@Query(name = "User.findByEmail")
User findByEmail(@Param("email") String email);
79.What is the difference between findById and
getOne methods in Spring Data JPA?
findById: Fetches the entity from the database immediately and
returns an Optional of the entity. If the entity does not exist,
it returns an empty Optional.
getOne: Returns a reference to the entity identified by the
given ID without fetching it immediately (lazy loading). The
actual database query is executed only when the returned entity
is accessed.

107.What does SPEL mean?
Spring Expression Language (SpEL) is a powerful feature of the
Spring framework that allows you to dynamically evaluate
expressions within the Spring container. SpEL supports querying
and manipulating an object graph at runtime.
108.what are the key features of SPEL?
Key Features of SpEL
Literal Expressions:
#{1 + 1} evaluates to 2.
#{'Hello' + ' World'} evaluates to Hello World.
Property Access:
#{person.name} accesses the name property of the person
object.
Method Invocation:
#{person.getName()} invokes the getName method on the person
object.
Arithmetic Operations:
#{1 + 2 * 3} evaluates to 7.
#{10 / 2} evaluates to 5.
Logical Operations:
SPRING TECHIE
#{true and false} evaluates to false.
#{10 > 5} evaluates to true.
Relational Operators:
#{5 > 2} evaluates to true.
#{5 == 5} evaluates to true.
Conditional Operators (Ternary Operator):
#{age > 18 ? 'Adult' : 'Minor'} evaluates based on the age
value.
Regex Matching:
#{'Hello' matches '[A-Za-z]+'} evaluates to true.
Collections:
#{list[0]} accesses the first element of a list.
#{map['key']} accesses the value associated with 'key' in a
map.
109.What is the @Value Annotation?
@Value is a core annotation in Spring that is primarily used for
assigning default values to variables and method parameters. It
also offers developers the capability to inject values from
property files into class members such as fields and method
parameters.
Example:
# assign the values that reading from properties file
@Value("${app.name}")
private String appName;
# assign the default values
SPRING TECHIE
@Value("${app.version:1.0}")
private String appVersion;
110.What are the Limitations of @Value ?
1. Type Safety: @Value is not type-safe. It doesn't provide
any compile-time checks; thus, any errors related to
property resolution will only occur at runtime.
2. Refactoring: If you refactor your properties (like changing
their names), you'll need to manually update all @Value
references.
3. Support for complex data structures: While @Value supports
Lists and Maps, the configuration can get messy for more
complex data structures.
These limitations have led to the recommendation of using
@ConfigurationProperties for complex use cases, or when type
safety and autocompletion are needed.

122.Can you tell me diff btw
@RestController & @Controller?
@Controller
Purpose: The @Controller annotation is used to mark a class
as a Spring MVC controller.
Responsibility: Controllers annotated with @Controller are
typically responsible for handling user requests,
processing them, and returning the appropriate view (HTML
page) or data (JSON, XML, etc.) to the client.
Default Behavior: By default, methods in @Controller
classes assume that they are returning a view name, which
is resolved by a view resolver to an actual view template
(HTML/JSP).
Use : @Controller when you need to render views and return
HTML pages in response to client requests in a traditional
web application.
@RestController
Purpose: The @RestController annotation is a specialized
version of @Controller.
Responsibility: Controllers annotated with @RestController
are responsible for handling RESTful web services. They
automatically serialize the return value (typically JSON or
XML) directly into the HTTP response body.
Default Behavior: Methods in @RestController classes do not
return a view name. Instead, they return the actual object
that will be serialized into JSON/XML and sent back as an
HTTP response.
Use : @RestController when you are building RESTful web
services and need to serialize Java objects directly into
JSON or XML.

124.Explain the concept of content
negotiation in RESTful APIs?
It's the process of selecting the best representation for a
given response when there are multiple representations available
(e.g., JSON, XML, HTML).
Clients and servers communicate their preferred content types
using request headers (Accept and Content-Type). The server then
selects and returns the representation that best matches the
client's preferences.
125.What are idempotent methods in
RESTful APIs? Give examples?
Operations that produce the same result regardless of how many
times they are repeated with the same input parameters. In REST:
GET: Retrieving a resource is idempotent because multiple
identical requests yield the same response.
PUT: Updating a resource is idempotent because sending the
same update multiple times has the same effect as sending
it once.
DELETE: Deleting a resource is idempotent because deleting
a resource that is already deleted or does not exist has no
additional effect.

126.What is API versioning and how can
you achieve it?
Api versioning allows us to maintain backward compatibility
while introducing new features or modifications without
hampering existing customers:
1. URI Versioning: The version number is included in the URL
path.
ex: /api/v1/resource
2. Query Parameter Versioning: The version number is included
as a query parameter.
ex: /api/resource?version=1
3. Header Versioning: The version number is specified in the
request header.
ex: application/vnd.api.v1+json
4. Content Negotiation Versioning: The version number is part
of the Accept header.
ex: Accept:application/vnd.api.v1+json

136.What are Database Transactions?
A Database transaction is a single logical unit of work which
accesses and possibly modifies the contents of a database. It
can be considered as a sequence of Queries that should be run in
a sequence performing one logical function.
137.Explain the ACID properties in the
context of transaction management?
ACID stands for Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and
Durability:
Atomicity: Ensures that all operations within a transaction
are completed successfully; if not, the transaction is
aborted and the database is left unchanged.
Consistency: Ensures that a transaction transforms the
database from one valid state to another, maintaining
database integrity.
Isolation: Ensures that transactions are executed in
isolation from each other, preventing concurrent
transactions from interfering with each other.
Durability: Ensures that once a transaction is committed,
its changes are permanent and will survive system failures.
138. How does transaction management
work in Spring Framework?
In Spring Framework, transaction management can be handled
declaratively using annotations or XML configuration, and
programmatically using the PlatformTransactionManager interface.
Commonly used annotations include @Transactional, which can be
SPRING TECHIE
applied to methods or classes to define the transaction scope.
Spring supports various transaction propagation behaviors (e.g.,
REQUIRED, REQUIRES_NEW) and isolation levels (e.g.,
READ_COMMITTED, SERIALIZABLE).
139.What is the difference between
programmatic and declarative
transaction management?
Programmatic Transaction Management: Involves explicitly
managing transactions in the code using APIs. This approach
provides fine-grained control but can lead to verbose and
error-prone code.
Declarative Transaction Management: Involves using configuration
(annotations or XML) to define transaction boundaries. This
approach separates transaction management from business logic,
leading to cleaner and more maintainable code.
140.What are Transaction Isolation
Levels?
READ_UNCOMMITTED: Allows transactions to read data that has been
modified but not yet committed by other transactions, which can
lead to dirty reads.
READ_COMMITTED: Ensures that a transaction can only read data
that has been committed by other transactions, preventing dirty
reads.
REPEATABLE_READ: Guarantees that if a transaction reads the same
row twice, it will see the same data both times, preventing
dirty reads and non-repeatable reads.
SERIALIZABLE: Provides the highest level of isolation by
ensuring that transactions are executed in a completely isolated
SPRING TECHIE
manner, preventing dirty reads, non-repeatable reads, and
phantom reads.
DEFAULT: Uses the default isolation level defined by the
database management system, which varies depending on the
specific DBMS.
141.What are the different types of
Transaction Propagations?
In Spring Boot, transaction propagation defines how a
transactional method should behave in relation to an existing
transaction.
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.MANDATORY)
public void method()
{
}
REQUIRED: Ensures that the method participates in an existing
transaction or starts a new one, making it suitable for most
business operations.
SUPPORTS: Provides flexibility to execute with or without a
transaction, useful for read-only or optional transactional
operations.
NOT_SUPPORTED: Ensures that the method executes outside of any
transaction, useful for operations that should not be
transactional.
REQUIRES_NEW: Creates a new, independent transaction, useful for
operations that need to be isolated from the outer transaction.
NEVER: Ensures strict non-transactional execution, useful for
methods that must not be part of any transaction.
MANDATORY: Enforces participation in an existing transaction,
ensuring that the method does not execute without a transaction.
SPRING TECHIE
142.Can I add @Transactional at class
level and method level then what is the
difference?
@Transactional at Class Level
When you apply @Transactional at the class level, all public methods in
the class inherit the transactional settings. This provides a convenient
way to ensure that all methods within the class are transactional without
having to annotate each one individually and the whole class is treated
as one transaction unit.
If any of the methods fails , it will rollback the method's actions.
@Transactional at Method Level
When you apply @Transactional at the method level, it applies to that
specific method only. This allows for fine-grained control over
transactional behavior on a per-method basis. Method-level annotations can
override class-level annotations if both are present.

SPRING TECHIE
propagation: Determines how transactions relate to each
other. For example, REQUIRES_NEW starts a new transaction,
while REQUIRED joins an existing one if available.
isolation: Defines the degree to which the operations in
one transaction are isolated from those in other
transactions. Higher levels of isolation reduce concurrency
issues but can impact performance.
timeout: Specifies the maximum time in seconds that a
transaction can run before it is automatically rolled back
by the transaction manager.
readOnly: Optimizes the transaction for read-only
operations, allowing the transaction manager and underlying

method.
noRollbackForClassName: Similar to noRollbackFor but allows
specifying exception class names as strings.

146.What is caching and why is it

Caching is the process of storing copies of data in a temporary
storage location (cache) so that it can be accessed faster. It
is important in web applications because it reduces the load on
the backend servers, decreases latency, and improves response
times by serving frequently accessed data from the cache instead
of recalculating or fetching it from the database every time.

In the case of Redis, you can set the TTL (Time To Live) for
cache entries using the @Cacheable annotation's cacheManager
property and configuring the CacheManager bean accordingly.
